56
Beneath The Surface
Sunday, June 29, 2025 10:00 am 1:00:12
Guest:
Alan Minsky
Topics
Mamdani’s spectacular NYC Mayoral Primary victory
Zohran Mamdani, a 33-year-old New York State Assembly member and democratic socialist, has just pulled off a historic upset—defeating Andrew Cuomo in the Democratic primary for mayor of New York City.

Despite being outspent 4 to 1, Mamdani’s campaign galvanized record turnout in triple-digit heat, powered by years of grassroots organizing among young progressives, immigrants, and working-class New Yorkers. His inclusive platform – emphasizing affordability – and visionary campaign won the day against the status quo, and set off alarm bells in the ossified Democratic establishment.

Mamdani is the first Muslim and South Asian nominee for mayor of New York, and the first democratic socialist in generations with a real chance to lead America’s largest city. He won support across nearly every constituency—from working-class neighborhoods to communities long pushed to the party’s margins.

Can this victory be replicated across the country? What can we learn from this campaign?

Alan Minsky—just back from New York, where he worked on Mamdani’s campaign, joins us to talk about how Mamdani won, what it means for New York, the left, the future of the Democratic Party, -- and social democratic reforms across the country.

Polish Election and the Global Far Right
David Ost on Poland’s stunning June 1 presidential election.The race was tight, but in the end, Karol Nawrocki, the far-right, hardline nationalist with MAGA-style politics and Trump’s backing, narrowly defeated Warsaw's liberal mayor Rafał Trzaskowski.
After recent electoral defeats for Trumpist candidates in Canada, Australia, and Romania, it seemed an international anti-Trump bump was underway. But Polish voters, just two years after electing liberal leader Donald Tusk, have swung back to the right. What does this election reveal about the continuing attraction of the authoritarian-nationalist-populist right to working class voters?
Ost argues Tusk overpromised and underdelivered, dampening turnout—echoing Biden/Harris’s troubles in the U.S. Meanwhile, the liberal left ran against Nawrocki’s negative personal qualities and tough working class background, not his reactionary, xenophobic agenda—feeding class resentment and fueling the far right.
Populism has shown to have staying power, and center left liberal governance has failed to offer a durable counter. Is Poland a warning to left liberals everywhere? And what are the implications for Ukraine, Europe and the globe?

Ost argues that Tusk in power promised a program of radical changes, but delivered too little, dampening enthusiasm and turnout, not unlike what happened to Biden and Harris. He also argues that the liberal left campaigned on Nawrocki’s negative personal qualities, including his tough working class background, rather than his reactionary, xenophobic policies – missteps that fed class resentment and fueled the far right.
Populism has shown to have staying power, and center left liberal governance has failed to offer a durable counter. Is Poland a warning to left liberals everywhere? And what are the implications for Ukraine, Europe and the globe. KPFK 90.7FM, streaming live and archived at www.kpfk.org

John Dinges
Topic
The Americans Disappeared by Pinochet
Journalist and author John Dinges joins us to discuss his new book "Chile in Their Hearts: The Untold Story of Two Americans Who Went Missing After the Coup."
Dinges lived in Chile from 1972-78, from the heady days of Allende’s Popular Unity government to the years of terror following the coup of September 11, 1973. His book reopens the case of Charles Horman and Frank Teruggi—two young Americans who went to Chile to participate in the democratic socialist process of President Salvador Allende’s Popular Unity government. They were disappeared -- went ‘missing,’ and were executed in the days following the military takeover.
Their story inspired the Oscar-winning film "Missing," which depicted Horman as the man who knew too much about U.S. involvement in the coup. But "Chile in Their Hearts" challenges that version as a myth—and uncovers the sham investigation and coverup behind its conclusions.

Malcom X Centennial Programming
Monday, May 19, 2025 1:00 pm 2:00:21
Host:
Malcolm X Centennial Programming on KPFK
Guest:
Malcolm X from the Pacifica Radio Archives
Topic
Malcolm X Centennial
KPFK celebrates the Centennial of Malcolm X Monday May 19, 2025 1-3pm with 2 talks from the Pacifica Radio Archives.
The Ballot or the Bullet Recorded in Detroit, 1964
Produced by Charles Hobson and Roberta Kurland.
This is one of Malcolm X's best-known speeches. In it, Malcolm X demonstrates the vision which contributed greatly to the new military within Black organizations, particularly SNCC and CORE, as well as to a new international perspective in the Black liberation movement.
A Choice of Two Roads Originally broadcast on WBAI circa 1960
Moderated by John Donald
Malcolm X, Bayard Rustin, and John Donald discuss the direction of the civil rights movement and its choices as seen from the perspective of the mid-60's.. Today, on what would’ve been Malcolm X’s 100th birthday, we honor a revolutionary who taught us Black liberation.
